data.content:
Yes — two better options depending on your MSTest version:

**1. `[DataRow]` — simplest for inline constants:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**2. Strongly-typed `DynamicData` (MSTest 3.7+) — when you need computed data:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Why these are better:**
- **`DataRow`**: No separate property needed, parameters are compile-time checked, but limited to constant values.
- **Typed `DynamicData`**: Eliminates `object[]` boxing/casting, gives compile-time type safety, and supports computed values. Requires MSTest **3.7+**.

Use `[DataRow]` for simple cases; use typed `DynamicData` when test data is dynamic or complex.
